# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: buffalo-braves
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The 1970–71 NBA season was the **Buffalo Braves** inaugural season in the NBA.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] With a roster made up primarily of castoffs, the Braves got off on the right foot by beating the Cleveland Cavaliers 107–92 at the Buffalo Memorial Auditorium on October 14.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] However, the Braves would drop their next nine as they took on established NBA teams on the way to finishing in last place in the Atlantic Division.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves' record was 22–60, which was 7 games better than the Cleveland Cavaliers, their partners in expansion.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] This was the only season that the team would wear blue, red, and gold, as the following season saw them change their jerseys to black and orange, which they would wear for the next two seasons.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The 1970 NBA draft was held on March 23, 1970, in New York City.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves first ever draft pick was John Hummer from Princeton, as he was selected with the 15th overall selection at the 1970 NBA draft.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Hummer, a 6'9" center from Washington, DC, averaged 17.5 points per game in 25 games with the Tigers during the 1969–70 season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Hummer led Princeton with a .487 field goal percentage, as well as leading the team with 9.5 rebounds per game.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Cornell Warner was selected by Buffalo in the second round, 24th overall.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Warner, another center, played for Jackson State University from 1967 to 1970.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The 1970 NBA expansion draft was held on May 11, 1970, with the Braves and two other expansion franchises, the Cleveland Cavaliers and the Portland Trail Blazers participating in the event.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves most notable selection was power forward Bailey Howell from the Boston Celtics.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Howell was a six time NBA all-star, however, immediately after the draft, he was traded to the Philadelphia 76ers in exchange for power forward Bob Kauffman, who had played the 1969-70 season with the Chicago Bulls.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Kauffman saw limited playing time with the Bulls, averaging 4.3 points per game while averaging 12.1 minutes per game in 64 games with Chicago.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Another selection was 10-year NBA veteran, forward/center Ray Scott from the Baltimore Bullets.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves management were looking forward to his leadership on the team; however, due to contradictory language in his Baltimore contract that provided him a loophole to become a free agent after the 1969-70 NBA season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves did not exercise his option under the reserve clause because they believed it was a two-year contract.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Scott was free to sign with the Virginia Squires in the American Basketball Association.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The league compensated the Braves due to losing a chosen player from Expansion Draft by promoting their 3rd round pick to a 2nd round pick (24th overall) in the 1971 NBA Draft.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves won their first game in franchise history, defeating the Cleveland Cavaliers 107–92 at the Buffalo Memorial Auditorium on October 14, 1970.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Don May led Buffalo with 24 points in the historic victory.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] This would be the Braves only victory in the month of October, as they closed out the month on a six-game losing streak.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] On October 24, May scored 34 points in a 114–95 loss to the Detroit Pistons.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Buffalo had a 1–6 record during the month, sitting in last place in the Atlantic Division, six games behind the first place New York Knicks.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Buffalo dropped their first three games of November, extending their losing skid to nine games and dropping the team to a 1–9 record.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves snapped their losing streak with a 103–91 victory over the Cleveland Cavaliers on November 7, which was the second time Buffalo had defeated Cleveland in the season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Bob Kauffman led the way for Buffalo with 24 points in 30 minutes.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] In their following game, Buffalo won consecutive games for the first time in team history, defeating the Atlanta Hawks 134–118, as Kauffman scored 35 points to lead the team, while Bill Hosket grabbed 17 rebounds.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] After dropping their next two games, the Braves returned to the win column with a 112–103 win over the Seattle SuperSonics on November 16, as Don May led the team in scoring with 25 points and John Hummer recorded a double-double with 10 points and 12 rebounds.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] On the next night, the Braves won their first ever road game, as they defeated the Portland Trail Blazers 102–101.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves struggled during the rest of the month, earning a 2–5 record over their remaining seven games, with wins over the Phoenix Suns and Portland Trail Blazers.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] In their win over Phoenix, Kauffman recorded a triple-double, as he scored 26 points, grabbed 17 rebounds, and recorded 11 assists in the 112–106 win.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves finished November with a 6–10 record during the month.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Overall, their record was 7–16, as the club remained in the Atlantic Division cellar, 11 games behind the first place New York Knicks.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Also during this time, the Braves traded guard Freddie Crawford to the Philadelphia 76ers for a future draft pick.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Buffalo began December with a narrow 117–116 loss to the Boston Celtics.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves returned to the win column on December 4, defeating the powerful New York Knicks 97–91, as Dick Garrett led the team with 23 points and 10 rebounds.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Bob Kauffman scored 22 points and recorded 13 rebounds, while Don May scored 20 points with 10 rebounds in the win.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Following the victory over New York, the Braves lost their next five games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] In the Braves 108–106 loss to the Cleveland Cavaliers, Kauffman scored 40 points, which was the first time in team history that a player reached 40 points in a game.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] On December 12, the Braves returned to the win column, beating the Detroit Pistons 93–92.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] After a loss to Atlanta in their next game, the Braves defeated the Los Angeles Lakers 113–111 in overtime, as Kauffman led the way with 34 points and 11 rebounds.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves lost their next game against Boston, but returned to the win column in their following game, crushing the Cleveland Cavaliers 113–94.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] In their win, six different Braves players recorded 10 or more points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Buffalo struggled for the remainder of the month, losing their final seven games of December.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The club recorded a 4–15 record in December, bringing their overall win–loss record to 11–31 at the end of the month.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves continued to be in last place in the Atlantic Division, 20 games behind the first place New York Knicks.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Buffalo lost their first game of the new year, losing 115–103 to the Cincinnati Royals, extending their losing skid to eight games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] In their next game, the Braves halted their losing streak with a 115–108 victory over the San Francisco Warriors, as Bob Kauffman led the way with 20 points and 17 rebounds.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Following the win over the Warriors, the Braves lost their next three games, including a 141–113 blowout loss to the Chicago Bulls.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Buffalo ended their losing streak with an impressive 119–113 win over the Portland Trail Blazers, in which eight players scored double digits in points for the Braves.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Buffalo then lost their next four games, including an embarrassing 111–79 loss to the Cleveland Cavaliers.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The club responded with a three-game winning streak after that loss to Cleveland, as the Braves defeated the Portland Trail Blazers twice, as well as a win over the San Diego Rockets.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Buffalo then concluded January on a five-game road trip, in which they lost every game.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Buffalo earned a record of 5-13 during the month of January.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Overall, the Braves were 16–44, falling to 24.5 games behind the Atlantic Division leaders, the New York Knicks.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Buffalo began February with two more losses in a row, extending their losing skid to seven games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The club ended their losing streak with a 106–99 victory over the New York Knicks, which was the Braves second victory over New York during the season, as Buffalo was led by Don May and his 29 points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] In their following game, the Braves defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers 111–106, as May led the team with 35 points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Following their two-game winning streak, Buffalo would end the month by dropping seven of their remaining eight games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Their lone win was a 118-114 decision over the Washington Bullets on February 17.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves finished February with a 3–9 record, dropping their overall win–loss record to 19–53, remaining in the Atlantic Division cellar and dropping to 27 games behind the first place New York Knicks.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves began March with a 131–118 loss to the Los Angeles Lakers.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] In the loss, Don May scored 40 points for Buffalo.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] In their next game, Buffalo dropped a close 116–113 game to the Milwaukee Bucks, extending their losing streak to seven games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves ended their losing streak and won their twentieth game of the season with a 120–109 victory over the Cleveland Cavaliers on March 6.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] In their following game, the Braves defeated the Portland Trail Blazers 114–98 to win consecutive games for the first time since the middle of February.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] After a loss to the San Diego Rockets, the Braves defeated the Los Angeles Lakers on the road 116–109 as seven different players earned 10 or more points for the Braves.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] Buffalo would finish the season with four straight losses.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves finished March with a 3–7 record, bringing their final regular season win–loss record to 22–60, finishing in fourth place in the four team Atlantic Division, 30 games behind the first place New York Knicks.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves missed the playoffs for the first inaugural season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves were involved in the following transactions during the 1970–71 season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nba-season] The **1970–71 NBA season** was the 25th season of the National Basketball Association.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nba-season] The season ended with the Milwaukee Bucks winning the NBA championship, beating the Baltimore Bullets 4 games to 0 in the NBA Finals.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nba-season] Three new teams made their debut: the Cleveland Cavaliers, the Portland Trail Blazers, and the Buffalo Braves.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The **1970–71 NHL season** was the 54th season of the National Hockey League.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Two new teams, the Buffalo Sabres and Vancouver Canucks made their debuts and were both put into the East Division.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Chicago Black Hawks were moved to the West Division, and the Oakland Seals were renamed the California Golden Seals.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Montreal Canadiens won the Stanley Cup by beating the Black Hawks in seven games in the Stanley Cup Final.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The NHL added two expansion teams in Buffalo and Vancouver.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The 1970 NHL expansion draft was held on June 10 to fill the rosters of the two new teams.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] At the beginning of the season, the Oakland Seals were renamed California Golden Seals.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The 1970 NHL amateur draft was held on June 11 at the Queen Elizabeth Hotel in Montreal, Quebec.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Gilbert Perreault was selected first overall by Buffalo.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] From this season through the 2002–03 season, teams wore their white (or yellow) jerseys at home and their colored jerseys on the road.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] For 1970–71 the NHL went to a balanced schedule, with each team playing each other team six times, three at home and three on the road, without regard to divisional alignment.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Nevertheless, playoff qualification was determined entirely by divisional standings, with the top four teams in each division qualifying.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] This season saw a marked increase in goal scoring, especially by the Boston Bruins, who shattered scoring records as they set the mark for most goals by a team (399) by nearly a hundred over the previous record holder.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] They also set records for most victories (57) and points (121).
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Phil Esposito set records for most goals in a season with 76 and for most points with 152.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Defenceman Bobby Orr won his second consecutive Hart Memorial Trophy and set a new record for assists with 102.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Bruins also had the four league leading scorers, the first time in history this was achieved (the only other time being by the Bruins in 1973–74), and seven of the top eleven leading scorers, the only time in NHL history this has ever been achieved.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] They had 6 of the top 8 scorers in the league.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Furthermore, the Bruins set marks for the highest scoring single season marks at every position: center (Esposito), left wing (Johnny Bucyk with 116), right wing (Ken Hodge with 105) and defence (Orr), as well as for a forward line (Esposito centering Wayne Cashman and Hodge).
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Boston won the East Division championship in a runaway.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] In the West Division, the powerful Chicago Black Hawks had been moved there partially to accommodate the expansion Buffalo Sabres and Vancouver Canucks (both of which were placed in the East Division) but more in an effort to provide greater balance between the divisions.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Louis' stranglehold over the division, winning handily over the Blues and advancing to the Stanley Cup Final.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Montreal Canadiens, who missed the playoffs in 1969–70, appeared to be sinking once more.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Players did not like Claude Ruel's dictatorial rule as coach, and Ralph Backstrom and John Ferguson retired.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Both Ferguson and Backstrom returned, but Backstrom was later traded to Los Angeles for draft choices.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Despite this, they would later win the Stanley Cup that year.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Vancouver Canucks played well at first and were around the .500 mark at mid-season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Then Orland Kurtenbach was injured and the team sagged.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] On October 29, Gordie Howe became the first player to record 1,000 assists in a 5–3 win over Boston at the Detroit Olympia.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Detroit introduced a fine rookie goaltender, Jim Rutherford, who had bright moments despite the Red Wings last place finish.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] However, they suffered their worst defeat in franchise history January 2, when Toronto crushed them 13–0.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Sid Abel, the team's general manager, asked owner Bruce Norris if he could dismiss coach Ned Harkness.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Norris then elevated Harkness to general manager and Doug Barkley was named coach.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Detroit took a tumble to the basement of the East Division after that.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] On March 12, Boston's Phil Esposito broke Bobby Hull's record for goals by a player in a season at 7:03 of the first period on Denis DeJordy of Los Angeles at the Forum in Inglewood, California.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Then, at 15:40 he became the first player to score 60 goals.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] In their inaugural season in the NHL, Buffalo had a star in Gilbert Perreault.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] On March 18, he broke Nels Stewart's (and Danny Grant's, and Norm Ferguson's) rookie record with his 35th goal in a 5–3 win over St.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] He went on to finish the season with 38.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Billy Taylor and Don Gallinger, now middle-aged, were finally forgiven for their gambling in 1948 and were reinstated to the NHL.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] However, they did not return to the NHL.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Due to three straight years of non-competitive finals (where the West Division winning St.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Louis Blues were swept all 3 years by an established East Division club); the NHL changed the match-ups for the semifinals by having the winner of the series of the 1st vs.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] 3rd East Division teams play the winner of the 2nd vs.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Similarly, the other semifinal series pitted the winner of the 1st vs.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] 3rd West Division teams against the winner of the 2nd vs.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Combined with the transfer of the Chicago Black Hawks into the West Division (which previously consisted only of expansion teams), the Stanley Cup Final series was expected to be more competitive.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The realignment and change in playoff format brought the desired results, but at the expense of the expansion teams; seven of the eight finalists were Original Six teams over the next four seasons.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Until realignment in 1974–75 when the Original Six and expansion teams were more thoroughly mixed, the Philadelphia Flyers were the only expansion team to reach a Cup final, which they won in 1974.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] A significant controversy arose before the playoffs.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] With 4 games to play, the Minnesota North Stars were in 3rd place with a record of 28–30–16 for 72 points while the Philadelphia Flyers were in 4th at 26–33–15 for 67 points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Minnesota then lost their final four games while the Flyers went 2–0–2 to jump ahead of Minnesota in the final standings by 1 point.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] It was widely rumored that Minnesota did so to avoid playing the far superior Chicago Black Hawks, since at this time in the playoffs the first place team played the third place team and the second played the fourth.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Nothing was proven against the North Stars (who defeated their first round opponents, St.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Louis, four games to two, while the Flyers were swept by the powerful Black Hawks), but the format was changed the next year to the 1 vs.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Boston Bruins finished first in the league with 121 points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Montreal Canadiens finished third in the East Division with 97 points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] This was the fifteenth playoff series between these two teams with Montreal winning twelve of the fourteen previous series.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] They last met in the 1969 Stanley Cup semifinals which Montreal won in six games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Boston won five of the six games in this year's regular season series.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Montreal Canadiens were matched against the Boston Bruins, and in one of the most extraordinary upsets in hockey history, Ken Dryden was hot in goal for the Canadiens as they ousted the Bruins in seven games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Game 2 featured what many perceive as one of the greatest comebacks in NHL history.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] With the Bruins leading 5–2 heading into the third period, the Canadiens, who had trailed 5–1, scored 5 goals in the final session to win 7–5.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The prominent Canadian sports journalist Red Fisher lists the Canadiens' comeback has the 8th most memorable moment in his over 49 years of covering hockey.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] In game 4, Bobby Orr became the first defenceman to get a hat trick in a playoff game when Boston won 5–2.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The New York Rangers finished second in the East Division with 109 points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Toronto Maple Leafs finished fourth with 82 points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] This was the eighth playoff meeting between these two teams with New York winning four of the seven previous series.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] They last met in the 1962 Stanley Cup semifinals which Toronto won in six games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] New York won five of the six games in this year's regular season series.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Chicago Black Hawks finished first in the West Division with 107 points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Philadelphia Flyers finished third in the West Division with 73 points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] This was the first playoff meeting between these two teams.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Chicago won this year's six game regular season series earning nine of twelve points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Louis Blues finished second in the West Division with 87 points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Minnesota North Stars finished fourth in the West Division with 72 points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] This was the third playoff meeting between these two teams with St.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Louis winning both of the previous series.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] They met in the previous year's Stanley Cup quarterfinals which the Blues won in six games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Minnesota won this year's six game regular season series earning eight of twelve points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] This was the first playoff series between these two teams.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Montreal won this year's six game regular season series earning eight of twelve points.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Canadiens' upset of Boston was so sensational that the Canadiens nearly suffered a fatal letdown against the Minnesota North Stars.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Canadiens' 6–3 loss in Montreal on April 22 to Minnesota, led by the goaltending of Cesare Maniago was the first playoff defeat for an Original Six team at the hands of a 1967 Expansion franchise.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] This was the third playoff series between these two teams with Chicago winning both previous series.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] They last met in the 1968 Stanley Cup quarterfinals which the Black Hawks won in six games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The teams split this year's six-game regular season series.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Bobby Hull and the Chicago Black Hawks were just too much for the Rangers and the Black Hawks advanced to the Stanley Cup Final in seven games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Hull won two games with goals on face-offs, despite Glen Sather's coverage to check him.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] This was the fifteenth series between these two teams with the Montreal Canadiens winning nine of the fourteen previous series.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] They last met in the 1968 Stanley Cup semifinals which Montreal won in five games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The series went the full seven games, with the Canadiens winning in Chicago despite trailing 2–0 halfway into the second period of game seven.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Jacques Lemaire took a shot from centre ice that miraculously escaped goaltender Tony Esposito cutting the Black Hawks' lead to 2–1.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Henri Richard tied the game just before the end of the second period, and scored again 02:34 into the third, giving the Habs the lead.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Montreal goalie Ken Dryden kept Chicago off the board for the rest of the game, and the Habs won their third Stanley Cup in four years.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] It was the final game for Canadiens superstar and captain Jean Beliveau who retired after the season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] The Canadiens were the last road team to win a Game 7 of a Stanley Cup Final until the Pittsburgh Penguins in 2009.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] It was Al MacNeil's final game as Montreal coach — after he had benched Richard for Game 5, The Pocket Rocket declared "[MacNeil] is the worst coach I ever played for!" Although Richard retracted his "angry comment", as he called it, MacNeil still resigned.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] A new award for the most outstanding player as voted by the members of the NHL Players Association, the Lester B.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] Pearson Award, was introduced this season and the first winner was Phil Esposito.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] This was the fifth season under the U.S. rights agreement with CBS, airing Sunday afternoon regular season and playoff games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-71-nhl-season] CBS also televised Game 7 of the 1971 Stanley Cup Final on a Thursday night, marking the first time an American network televised an NHL prime time game, but the telecast was blacked out in the Chicago Black Hawks' broadcast territory.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] The **1970 NBA draft** was the 24th annual draft of the National Basketball Association (NBA).
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] The draft was held on March 23, 1970, before the 1970–71 season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] In this draft, 17 NBA teams took turns selecting amateur U.S. college basketball players and other eligible players, including international players.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] A player who had finished his four-year college eligibility was eligible for selection.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] If a player left college early, he would not be eligible for selection until his college class graduated.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] The first two picks in the draft belonged to the teams that finished last in each division, with the order determined by a coin flip.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] The Detroit Pistons won the coin flip and were awarded the first overall pick, while the San Diego Rockets were awarded the second pick.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] The remaining first-round picks and the subsequent rounds were assigned to teams in reverse order of their win–loss record in the previous season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Three expansion franchises, the Buffalo Braves, the Cleveland Cavaliers and the Portland Trail Blazers, took part in the NBA Draft for the first time and were assigned the seventh, the eighth and the ninth pick in each round.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] In the first round, the Cavaliers had the seventh pick, while the Blazers and the Braves had the eighth and the ninth pick respectively.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] In the subsequent rounds, the Cavaliers and the Braves exchanged their order of selection, while the Blazers had the eighth pick throughout the draft.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] The draft consisted of 19 rounds comprising the selection of 239 players; it holds the record for the most prospects selected in any NBA draft.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Bonaventure University was selected first overall by the Detroit Pistons.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Rudy Tomjanovich from the University of Michigan and Pete Maravich from Louisiana State University were selected second and third, respectively.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Fourth pick Dave Cowens from Florida State University and eighth pick Geoff Petrie from Princeton University were joint winners of the Rookie of the Year Award in their first season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Six players from this draft, Lanier, Maravich, Cowens, 18th pick Calvin Murphy, 19th pick Nate Archibald, and 122nd pick Dan Issel, have been inducted to the Basketball Hall of Fame.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Maravich, Cowens, and Archibald were also named to the list of the 50 Greatest Players in NBA History at the league's 50th anniversary in 1996.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Maravich had four All-NBA Team selections and five All-Star Game selections.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Cowens won two NBA championships with the Boston Celtics in 1974 and 1976, one Most Valuable Player Award in 1973, and had three All-NBA Team selections and seven All-Star Game selections.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Archibald won one NBA championship with the Celtics in 1981 and had five All-NBA Team selections and six All-Star Game selections.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Lanier and Murphy were selected to eight and one All-Star Games, respectively.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Issel initially opted to play in the American Basketball Association (ABA) with the Kentucky Colonels.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] He played six seasons in the ABA before finally joining the NBA with the Denver Nuggets when both leagues merged.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] He was selected to five All-ABA Teams, six ABA All-Star Games, and one NBA All-Star Game.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Randy Smith, who was selected by the Detroit Pistons with the 205th pick, did not enter the league until the 1971–72 season, after he was drafted again in the 1971 NBA draft by the Buffalo Braves with the 104th pick.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] He was selected to both the All-NBA Team and the All-Star Game.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Tomjanovich was selected to five All-Star Games during his career.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Charlie Scott, the 106th pick, initially played in the ABA with the Virginia Squires before joining the NBA in 1972.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] He was selected to two All-ABA Teams, two ABA All-Star Games, and three NBA All-Star Games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Three other players from this draft, fifth pick Sam Lacey, seventh pick John Johnson, and eighth pick Geoff Petrie, were also selected to at least one All-Star Game.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] The Rockets' first and second-round picks, Tomjanovich and Murphy spent all of their playing career with the Rockets.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Tomjanovich played 11 seasons while Murphy played 13 seasons with the Rockets.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Lanier, Tomjanovich, Cowens, and Issel all became head coaches after ending their playing career.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Lanier was the interim head coach of the Golden State Warriors in the 1995.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Tomjanovich coached two NBA teams, the Houston Rockets and the Los Angeles Lakers.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] He coached the Rockets for 12 seasons, leading them to the NBA championship twice in 1994 and 1995.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] He also coached the United States national basketball team to a gold medal at the 2000 Olympic Games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Cowens started his coaching career as a player-coach with the Celtics during the 1978–79 season, before returning to a full-time player in the next season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] He later coached two more NBA teams, most recently with the Golden State Warriors.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Issel coached the Denver Nuggets for six seasons in two separate three-year stints.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Two other players drafted also went on to have coaching careers in the NBA: 40th pick Gar Heard and 125th pick George Irvine.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] The 1970 draft class is considered to be one of the best in NBA history as it produced eight Hall of Famers and 12 All-Stars from those who played in the NBA.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] The first four picks were inducted to the Hall of Fame and seven of the first eight picks became All-Stars.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] The 1970 Draft also was the first draft where international players who had never played U.S. high school and college basketball were selected.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] In the 10th and 11th round, the Atlanta Hawks drafted Mexican Manuel Raga and Italian Dino Meneghin; both were playing in the Italian league at the time.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] They became the first two international players drafted to the NBA.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] However, neither played in the league as the Hawks did not have US$35,000 to buy out either of their contracts with their teams.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Meneghin, who played 28 seasons in Italy, has been inducted by the International Basketball Federation (FIBA) to the FIBA Hall of Fame and also to the Basketball Hall of Fame.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] Raga has also been inducted into the FIBA Hall of Fame.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-draft] These players were not selected in the 1970 draft but played at least one game in the NBA.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] The **1970 NBA expansion draft** was the fifth expansion draft of the National Basketball Association (NBA).
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] The draft was held on May 11, 1970, so that the newly founded Buffalo Braves, Cleveland Cavaliers, and Portland Trail Blazers could acquire players for the 1970–71 season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] Buffalo, Cleveland, and Portland were awarded the expansion teams on February 6, 1970.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] Houston was also awarded a franchise, but the group backing the team was unable to come up with the US$750,000 down payment on the US$3.7 million entrance fee that was required before the 1970 NBA draft.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] The Braves later underwent two relocations, moving to San Diego in 1978 and changing their name from the Braves to the Clippers, and then relocating to Los Angeles in 1984.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] They are currently known as the Los Angeles Clippers.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] In an NBA expansion draft, new NBA teams are allowed to acquire players from the previously established teams in the league.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] Not all players on a given team are available during an expansion draft, since each team can protect a certain number of players from being selected.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] In this draft, each of the other fourteen NBA teams protected seven players from their roster.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] After each round, after all of the expansion teams had selected one player, each of the existing teams added another player to their protected list.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] In the first round, the Braves had the first pick, while the Blazers and the Cavaliers had the second and the third picks respectively.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] In the subsequent rounds, the Braves and the Cavaliers exchanged their order of selection, while the Blazers had the second pick throughout the draft.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] The draft continued until all three teams had selected eleven unprotected players each, while the existing teams had lost two or three players each.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] The Buffalo Braves were formed and owned by local businessman Paul Snyder.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] He hired former Philadelphia 76ers head coach and 1966 Coach of the Year Dolph Schayes as the franchise's first head coach.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] The Braves' selections included six-time All-Star Bailey Howell.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] Howell was immediately traded to the 76ers, however, in exchange for Bob Kauffman and a future second-round pick.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] Nine players from the draft joined the Braves for their inaugural season, but only three played more than one season for the team.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] The Cleveland Cavaliers were formed and owned by businessman Nick Mileti.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] He hired former college basketball coach Bill Fitch as the franchise's first head coach.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] The Cavaliers' selections included five-time All-Star Don Ohl and one-time All-Star Len Chappell.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] Ohl retired from playing prior to the start of the season, however, and Chappell only played briefly before he was waived.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] Eight players from the draft joined the Cavaliers for their inaugural season, but only four played more than one season for the team.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] Butch Beard was the ninth player from the expansion draft to play for the Cavaliers.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] He joined the team for the 1971–72 season after serving for a year in the military.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] Bingo Smith played nine and a half seasons with the Cavaliers before he was traded to the San Diego Clippers in 1979.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] He was the franchise's leader in games played when he left, a record that stood until 2000 when Danny Ferry broke it.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] The Portland Trail Blazers were formed by Harry Glickman, who created the franchise through the financiers turned co-owners Larry Weinberg, Herman Sarkowsky and Robert Shmertz.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] They hired former college basketball coach Rolland Todd as the franchise's first head coach.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] The Blazers' selections included former first overall pick Fred Hetzel and former third pick Larry Siegfried.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] Hetzel was waived without playing a game for the Blazers, however, and Siegfried was immediately traded to the San Diego Rockets in exchange for Jim Barnett.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] Six players from the draft joined the Blazers for their inaugural season, but only three played more than one season for the team.
[src:buffalo-braves/1970-nba-expansion-draft] The Blazers also selected Pat Riley, who never played for the team, but went on to have a Hall of Fame coaching career, enshrined in 2008.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-buffalo-braves-season] The 1971–72 NBA season was the **Buffalo Braves'** second season in the NBA.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-buffalo-braves-season] A pair of rookies named Smith gave Buffalo fans reason for a bright future.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-buffalo-braves-season] On October 13, head coach Dolph Schayes was dismissed after losing the season opener and was replaced by Johnny McCarthy for the rest of the season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves repeated their 22–60 record from their inaugural season, and occupied the Atlantic Division basement.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-buffalo-braves-season] Elmore Smith and Randy Smith each had out standing rookie seasons with Elmore averaging 17.3 points per game and 15.2 rebounds per game, while Randy added 13.4 points per game.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-buffalo-braves-season] The Braves were involved in the following transactions during the 1971–72 season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] The **1971–72 NBA season** was the 26th season of the National Basketball Association.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] The season ended with the Los Angeles Lakers winning the NBA championship, beating the New York Knicks 4 games to 1 in the NBA Finals.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] As the 25th anniversary of the founding of the modern NBA, the league unveiled a new logo, inspired by the logo of Major League Baseball, to commemorate the occasion.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] It features the white silhouette of a basketball player dribbling, framed by red and blue.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] Jerry West of the Los Angeles Lakers was used as the model for the logo.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] Coincidentally, Jerry West would win the only NBA championship of his career during the season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] The Los Angeles Lakers came into the season returning a veteran squad from their playoff run a year before.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] Nine games into the season, aging and oft injured Elgin Baylor announced his retirement after 13 seasons.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] He was replaced at the starting small forward spot by Jim McMillian, who would go on to average 18 points per game, third best on the team.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] Despite Baylor's retirement, the Lakers went on a 33-game winning streak.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] The Lakers completed two undefeated months, going 14–0 in November and 16–0 in December.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] After winning their first three games in January, the Lakers lost 120–104 to the Milwaukee Bucks.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] On March 20, 1972, the Lakers beat Golden State by a record 63 points (162–99), a mark that would stand until 1991, when Cleveland beat Miami by 68 points (148–80) and later was broken in 2021 when Memphis beat Oklahoma City by 73 points (152–79).
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] The Lakers finished the season with a record 69 wins, which would stand until the 1995–96 season when the Chicago Bulls won 72 regular season games and later was also broken by the 2015–16 Golden State Warriors won an NBA record 73 regular season games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] The defending champion Milwaukee Bucks won 63 games on the play of renamed Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, formerly Lew Alcindor, and Oscar Robertson.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] The Celtics, led by second year center Dave Cowens, point guard Jo Jo White and 32-year-old swingman John Havlicek won the Atlantic Division with 56 wins.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] Boston had recovered from the retirement of Bill Russell, K.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] Jones and Sam Jones by winning 12 more games than the previous season.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] In the first round, the Lakers swept the Bulls and Milwaukee defeated Golden State.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] New York eliminated the Bullets and Boston won against the Atlanta Hawks.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] In the Western Conference Finals, the Lakers lost game 1 versus the defending champion Bucks at The Forum 93–72, a game that saw the Lakers score only 8 points in the third quarter.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] However, the Lakers led by assist champion Jerry West, leading scorer Gail Goodrich and veteran Wilt Chamberlain would win 4 of the next 5 games and beat Milwaukee in six games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] In the Eastern Conference Finals, New York defeated the top-seed Celtics in five games.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] In the NBA Finals, New York won game 1 very easily, but Los Angeles won game 2 106–92 to even the series.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] In game 3, the Lakers jumped out to a 22-point lead and regained home-court advantage with a 107–96 win.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] At the end of regulation, Wilt Chamberlain was called for his fifth foul.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] In his first 12 seasons, he had never fouled out of a game.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] Chamberlain did not foul out and led the Lakers to a 116–111 victory, but he broke his wrist in the overtime period.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] The Lakers held a 3–1 series lead going into game 5 in Los Angeles.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] In game 5, Chamberlain played despite his injury.
[src:buffalo-braves/1971-72-nba-season] The score was tied at 53 in the first half, but the Lakers outscored the Knicks 61–47 in the second half to win the game and the NBA championship, 114–100.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The **Buffalo Braves** were an American professional basketball team based in Buffalo, New York.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Founded in 1970, the Braves competed in the National Basketball Association (NBA) as a member of the Atlantic Division of the Eastern Conference.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Brown Jr. swapped franchises with then-Boston Celtics owner Irv Levin, who then moved the team to San Diego, where it was renamed the **San Diego Clippers**.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The franchise relocated to Los Angeles in 1984, becoming the Los Angeles Clippers.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The Braves were one of three NBA expansion teams that began to play in the 1970–71 season (the others being the Portland Trail Blazers and Cleveland Cavaliers).
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] It was originally owned by Neuberger Loeb, a New York City investment firm that had few ties to Buffalo.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] However, a series of missteps resulted in the league taking control of the team before it even played a preseason game.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] By opening night, Paul Snyder, a then 33-year-old entrepreneur who had recently cashed in on the sale of his Freezer Queen business, had bought the franchise for $4 million.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] They played their home games at the Buffalo Memorial Auditorium, sharing the arena with another new franchise, the National Hockey League (NHL)'s Buffalo Sabres, who also debuted in 1970, as well as local college basketball teams that had used the auditorium for decades prior.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The NBA had two previous teams in Upstate New York, the Rochester Royals and the Syracuse Nationals (who are now known as the Sacramento Kings and Philadelphia 76ers, respectively).
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] As of 2026, the Braves are the last New York State-based NBA team to be based somewhere other than New York City, where the New York Knicks and Brooklyn Nets play.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The team's first head coach was Hall of Famer Dolph Schayes and the franchise's first star players were Bob Kauffman and Don May, who were acquired in the 1970 NBA expansion draft.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] However, in the NBA draft of 1970, Buffalo passed on hometown hero Calvin Murphy, a 5-foot-9 point guard from Niagara University, and picked Princeton graduate John Hummer as their first round draft pick.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Murphy would eventually be inducted into the Hall of Fame.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] As is typical of first-year expansion teams, the Braves finished with a dismal record, 22–60, seven games ahead of the Cleveland Cavaliers, their expansion cousins, who finished at 15–67.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Kauffman, who averaged 4.3 points per game the previous year with the Chicago Bulls, led Buffalo in scoring with 20.4 points per game and earned a spot on the 1971 NBA Eastern Conference All-Star team.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The Braves repeated their 22–60 record in the 1971–72 season, but made acquisitions that would prove to improve the team.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Buffalo drafted center Elmore Smith from Kentucky State University and local favorite Randy Smith from Buffalo State College.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Johnny McCarthy replaced Schayes one game into the season as the team's head coach.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The team did slightly worse in the 1972–73 season, as it went 21–61 under new head coach Dr.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] In a showcase of the futility of the '72-'73 Braves, during the team's fifth game of the season on October 20, 1972, the team set an NBA record which still stands for most points in a single quarter with 58 in the fourth quarter against the Boston Celtics.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] However the Celtics were in the process of a blowout win and had already led the Braves 103–60 at the start of the quarter.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] They had inserted their substitutes to play the final quarter and the reduced quality of the opponents allowed for the comeback.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The Braves outscored the Celtics 58-23 but still lost 126–118.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The Braves' big move that season was drafting forward/center Bob McAdoo from North Carolina.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The team finally made its first playoff appearance in 1974, in which they faced the Celtics and lost in six games.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] That season, McAdoo posted averages of 30.6 points and 15.1 rebounds; this is the last time any player has averaged at least 30 points and 15 rebounds in the same NBA season.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Also, that season, the Braves rookie Ernie DiGregorio won the NBA Rookie of the Year Award.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] In 1974–75, McAdoo was awarded the NBA Most Valuable Player Award, averaging 34.5 points, 14.1 rebounds. and 2.12 blocks per game, while shooting 51.2% from the field and 80.5% from the free-throw line.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The Braves made trips to the playoffs in both 1974–75 and 1975–76, the latter of which would be their last playoff berth playing in Buffalo.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The Braves by this point were a modest success, both on the court and off; the team was drawing close to the league average in fans, had solid broadcasting ratings and was turning a consistent profit.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Even so, by 1976 Snyder was facing severe pressure to sell the team and get it out of Buffalo.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] As a result of the Braves only getting the third choice of dates at the Aud, the entire NBA was unable to finalize a schedule and hammer out television contracts until the Sabres and Griffins finalized their schedules.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The NBA considered this untenable, and gave Snyder five years to resolve the problem.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] In a 2016 interview with *The Buffalo News* as part of a retrospective on the Braves, Snyder laid particular blame on Canisius president Father James Demske for making it difficult to get good home dates at the Aud.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Snyder recalled offering Demske $125,000 per game to give up some Saturday night dates to the Braves.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] However, Demske turned the offer down, believing that the Braves posed a threat to the Little Three rivalry in college basketball.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] When the five-year deadline expired without a resolution, Snyder found himself with two options–build a new arena or sell the team.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Building a new arena wasn't financially realistic at the time, leaving Snyder with no option but to sell the team.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Had the dispute been resolved, the Braves would have likely been able to stay in Buffalo, especially since Canisius basketball went into what would be permanent decline in the early 1980s.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] At the time, Snyder's more public feuds were with the Sabres, whose owners, Northrup and Seymour Knox, represented Buffalo's old money circuit while Snyder had *nouveau riche* status.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Years later, Snyder attributed these feuds to his own inexperience with sports ownership and now speaks in more conciliatory tones regarding his hockey competition.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The June 15, 1976 issue of Buffalo's *Courier-Express* blasted the headline "Braves Go to Florida, Leaving 'Hockey Town'".
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Snyder had a handshake deal to sell the team for $6.1 million to hotel owner Irving Cowan, who would move the Braves to the Hollywood Sportatorium outside of Miami.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] However, the city of Buffalo filed a $10 million damage suit to block the move.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The sale eventually fell through and the Braves and the city signed a new 15-year Memorial Auditorium lease in July with a provision that the lease could be voided if the team did not sell 5,000 season tickets in any season.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Later that summer, Snyder finally sold 50% of the franchise to businessman John Y.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Brown Jr., who had previously owned the Kentucky Colonels of the American Basketball Association (ABA).
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Brown later acquired the remaining half from Snyder sometime in the 1976–77 season with the intention of reviving the Colonels by relocating the Braves to Louisville.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Unable to find a willing co-owner for such a venture, he resold the other stake to another businessman, Harry T.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Brown and Mangurian proceeded to dismantle the Braves.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Ramsay, unwilling to have his career hurt by the change in ownership, left for the Portland Trail Blazers, who would win the NBA championship in the upcoming 1976–77 season.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] A provision in the team sale agreement stipulated that if Brown sold the contract of any Braves player, then the money would go to Snyder and the purchase price would be reduced.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] This subsequently occurred when the Braves sent McAdoo to the New York Knicks for players and cash midway through the season.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Before the first game of the season, the Braves also managed to acquire eventual Hall-of-Fame center Moses Malone from Portland.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] However, after just two games in which he played a total of six minutes, he too was traded; he was sent to Houston for two draft picks.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] He would finish the season in Houston averaging 13 points and 13 rebounds while only two years later winning his first of three MVP Awards.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The Braves would go through four head coaches in the next two seasons: Tates Locke, Bob MacKinnon, Joe Mullaney (formerly coach of the Colonels) and Cotton Fitzsimmons.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The team's poor play in its final two years (30–52 in 1976–77 and 27–55 in 1977–78) and the overt attempts to break the lease on Memorial Auditorium drove attendance down below the threshold that would have been needed to break the lease.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Brown met with Irv Levin, who then owned the Celtics, and negotiated a deal in which the owners would swap franchises, with Brown taking control of the Celtics and Levin getting the Braves.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Levin was a California businessman, and wanted to own an NBA team in his native state.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] However, he knew the NBA would not even consider letting him move the Celtics.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] He was therefore very receptive to Brown's offer.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The deal was brokered by then NBA general counsel David Stern, who became the league's commissioner in 1984.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Following what would be the Braves' final season in Western New York, the NBA owners voted 21–1 to let the team move.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] As Levin wanted, he became owner of a team in San Diego after the 1977–78 season, which became the San Diego (now Los Angeles) Clippers.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] As part of the transaction, the teams traded most of the players on their rosters.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Brown would sell off the Celtics in 1979.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] For the franchise's first season (1970–71) team colors were blue, red & gold; home white uniforms featured lettering and striping in only red & gold, with road uniforms being blue, also with red & gold lettering and striping.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] In the second season, (1971–72) the team adopted the colors of the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] This was with the heavy influence of the local uniform supplier, James (Jim) Ludtka.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Ludtka was a former pro baseball player with the New York Yankees and was scouting for the Orioles organization.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The new color scheme was white, orange and black, with the now familiar "feather B" logo featured on uniforms that had diagonal stripes across both jerseys and shorts (the predominant color on the road being orange).
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] (Despite the new color scheme, the logo – which no longer appeared on the uniforms – remained the black and orange "feather B").
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The team's name, said at the time to be a tribute to the Seneca Nation of Indians, came well before the controversy of Native American names in sports beginning in the 1990s came to light, and the Braves nickname has been said to have been a "curse" upon the franchise from the start.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] The Clippers refused to relinquish the Braves trademark in 2005 when an expansion American Basketball Association franchise wanted to use it, so that team instead became the Buffalo Rapids.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] For most of the team's existence, WBEN (930 AM) was the radio home of the Buffalo Braves, with Van Miller on play-by-play.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Miller also called play-by-play on the team's telecasts over WBEN-TV (channel 4, now WIVB-TV), the local CBS television affiliate.
[src:buffalo-braves/buffalo-braves] Snyder claimed that the Braves broadcasts were drawing far higher ratings than the Sabres at the time and insisted that if he had managed to keep the Braves in Buffalo, the Sabres would have been the team eventually forced to move out of the city.
